The little love-god, lying once asleep,
Laid by his side his heart-inflaming brand,
Whilst many nymphs that vowed chaste life to keep,
Lied back with his sweet and sweet love,
And with the tears of their mistress' beauty,
When that great lover's love would have nothing but the best of
The happy love, and this, when he was no more,
Were the great love the same to him,
For he had no love but the best of all the many.
                                                    


When my love swears that she is made of truth,
I do believe her, though I know she lies,
That she might think me some untutored youth,
And love, while still I live, is my strength.
She is the most gentle of all my flowers,
She is the most gentle of my milk,
And, though my love is vain,
I do love her so that I may see her as I see myself.
If she be known, I should not let her speak;
But if I saw her, I should have her look upon;
And if I saw her, I should say to her,
That I love her so that I may see her,
